    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>"Mars" is now the common name used for synthetic iron oxide pigments. Mars colors are made from hydrated iron oxide co-precipitated with alum using lime or potash. The proportion of the mixture controls the degree of color; drying the product produces Mars yellow, other colors include orange, red, black, brown, and violet, produced by calcining the yellow. "Mars" was originally a brand name in the late 18th century.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000009521/Color: Universal Language and Dictionary (1976)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>「Mars」一字是現今對合成氧化鐵顏料的通名。其顏色是由含水的鐵氧化物，運用石灰或者是碳酸鉀共同沈澱所製成。此一混合物的比例控制了顏色的色度，若將成品晾乾，就會產生合成氧化鐵黃，其他顏色則包含橘色、紅色、黑色、棕色，以及將黃色鈣化所產生出的紫色。「Mars」一字原本是西元十八世紀晚期的一個品牌名稱。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
